           <h3>Pharmacy School Alamanac</h3>
           <p>
               Welcome! Applying to a pharmacy program can feel overwhelming. You need to worry about deadlines, essays, GPA's, test scores, letters of recommendation, and that's just the
               beginning! Hopefully this simple web app will help you organize your thoughts and sort through programs that best fit the needs of your professional goals. Here you can filter
               programs by location, how long the program is, whether it is associated with a hospital or other academic medical center, and whether the program is state supported or a private
               program. 
           </p>
           <p>
                From there, simply clicking on the row will take you to a page specifically about the your program with much more detailed information, such as application deadline, entrance 
                requirements, and how to find more information regarding the program and who you may contact with questions. 
           </p>
           <button type="button" class="btn btn-dark" onclick="toggleVisibility()">Things to Consider</button>
           <p></p>
           <div id="toggle" style="display: none;">
            <p>
                What is your current academic status? Are you almost finished with a degree or haven't even enrolled in higher education yet? Have you ever had experience working as 
                a pharmacy technician? What are your professional goals? Would you rather work in a clinical setting? A research setting? Traditional retail setting? These are all Things
                to think about because every pharmacy program is different and can help you with different things.  
            </p>
            <p>
                Not every program requires or even prefers a Bachelor's Degree. Many just want the prerequisite courses completed. Have you worked as a technician and want to advance
                to becoming a pharmacist? Then obtaining a degree may not be in your best interest. Some schools do not require no consider the Pharmacy College Admissions Test. Taking
                a semester to study for this entrance exam may not be worth your time if your goal is retail pharmacy. Finding a 3-Year program will help you find your job quicker while 
                teaching you all the necessary skills to succeed. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Conversely, is your goal research or working in a clinical setting such as a hospital? Then a degree will make you much more competitive. Taking time to prepare for the PCAT 
                be wise as top pharmacy programs can be very competitive and you'll want every edge to stand among a sea of applicants. Additionally, a 4 year program, particularly one associated 
                with an academic health center, will give you time and opportunities to prepare yourself for residency applications and interviews in your final year. 
            </p>      
            <p>
              These are only a few things to consider when choosing the pharmacy program that is best suited for you.   
            </p>    
